After some visual assesments, I found some issues with this dataset, some preliminary cleaning needs to be performed.¶

List of items to be cleaned¶

Fill missing values in [CurrentCreditLines, OpenCreditLines] with 0

Fill missing values in BorrowerState with 'N/A'

Fill missing values in Occupation with 'Not Available'

Fill missing values in EmploymentStatus with 'Not Available'

Fill missing values in EmploymentStatusDuration with 'Not Available'

Fill missing values in InquiriesLast6Months with 0

Fill missing values in DebtToIncomeRatio with 'Not Available'

In [ ]:
#Using a function to fill missing values with item
def missing_fill(column, item):
    column = column.fillna(item, inplace=True)

missing_fill(loan_data.CurrentCreditLines, 0.0)
missing_fill(loan_data.OpenCreditLines, 0)
missing_fill(loan_data.BorrowerState, 'N/A')
missing_fill(loan_data.Occupation, 'Not Available')
missing_fill(loan_data.EmploymentStatus, 'Not Available')
missing_fill(loan_data.EmploymentStatusDuration, 'Not available')
missing_fill(loan_data.InquiriesLast6Months, 0)
missing_fill(loan_data.DebtToIncomeRatio, 'Not Available')

#converting CurrentCreditLines to int64
loan_data.CurrentCreditLines = loan_data.CurrentCreditLines.astype('int64')

Through the visualizations above I managed to find the following:

  • Californians represents a large amount of the borrowers listed in this dataset
  • Most borrowers in this dataset have had between 15 to 25 open credit lines in the past 7 years.
  • Between 6 to 8 new credit lines were opened at the time of recording this dataset
  • Employed Borrowers make a large portion of the individuals in this dataset

#Plotting a chart depicting a relationship between LoanStatus and IncomeRange
#Preparing the columns for plotting
counts = loan_data.groupby(['LoanStatus', 'IncomeRange']).size()    
counts = counts.reset_index(name='Count')
counts.pivot(index='LoanStatus', columns='IncomeRange', values='Count')
#Combining the pastdue dates into one category
loan_data['LoanStatusNew'] = np.where(loan_data.LoanStatus.str.contains('Past Due'), "Past Due", loan_data.LoanStatus)
LoanStatus_ordered = ['Cancelled', 'Completed', 'FinalPaymentInProgress', 'Current', 'PastDue', 'Chargedoff', 'Defaulted']
IncomeRange_ordered = ['Not employed', '$0', '$1-24,999', '$25,000-49,999', '$50,000-74,999', '$75,000-99,999', '$100,000+', 'Not displayed']
#Setting up an order for the relevant variables
status_order=['Canceled', 'Completed', 'FinalPaymentInProgress', 'Current', ]
#plotting the columns using a clustered bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.countplot(data=loan_data, x='LoanStatusNew', hue='IncomeRange', order=LoanStatus_ordered, hue_order=IncomeRange_ordered)
plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=8)
plt.show();

From the visualizations above i deduced the following:

  • The number of new Credit lines is increasing as the years pass by, this is being indicated by the plot depiciting the relationship between Current Credit Lines and Total Credit lines in the Past 7 Years
  • We can also see a strong correlation between CurrentCreditLines and OpenCreditLines in the correlation matrix, this correlation is almost at a full 1, followed by a correlation between Total Credit lines in the Past 7 Years and Open Credit lines
  • We also notice that Borrowers with an income range between $25k-49k are more likely to have their loans completed, while borrowers with an income range of $50k-74k are more likely to have open loans. Interestingly, borrowers with an income range of above $100k are also more likely to keep their loans opened rather than complete them.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The major relationship I strived to investigate in this part is the effect of the number of current credit lines and recently open credit lines has on the credit grade, and unsurprisingly, the more current credit lines a borrower has opened in the past 7 years the better their credit grade is, although and surprisingly, the less current credit lines a borrower has opened the better their credit grade.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

No

Conclusions¶

As this dataset was large to do a complete investigation on, I limited my efforts to investigate a handful of features that helped me answer the questions i found most relevant above.

Although mostly clean, this dataset still needed adjustments such as datatype changes and cleaning some Not available items. Once cleaned, I then moved to plot the most relevant features and investigate their details to come up with meaningful conclusions. The investigation mainly yielded predictable results, and there were no surprising interactions in the features I investigated.
